article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 23 points Friday night to
lead the Detroit Shock to their fourth straight victory, a 77-67
win over the injury-plagued Seattle Storm.
article.headline: Nolan, Shock beat weakened Storm for fourth straight
article.linkText: Nolan, Shock beat weakened Storm for fourth straight
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Deanna Nolan scored 23 points Friday night to
lead the Detroit Shock to their fourth straight victory, a 77-67
win over the injury-plagued Seattle Storm.

Nolan scored 17 of her 23 points in the first half. Teammate
Cheryl Ford, the league's leading rebounder at 11.5 per game, had
18 points and 18 boards.

"Our offense is starting to come around," Detroit coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "Our defense has been there all year. We're the
best defensive field goal team in the league. We have size,
rebounding, quickness. We believe we are the team of destiny. We
have the best starting five anyone could ask for."

The Storm (14-13) played without leading scorer Lauren Jackson
in the second half because of plantar fasciitis in her left foot.
Betty Lennox, the team's second-leading scorer at 14.2 per game,
missed the final period with a sore right knee.

Storm center Cisti Greenwalt sustained a concussion on a hard
foul with 1:22 left in the third and had to be helped to the locker
room. She did not return to the floor.

"It's frustrating for everyone involved," said Jackson, the
former league MVP. "There is nothing I can do with this injury.
It's debilitating for me. It's not like it's a joint. It's a
muscle. It's pretty much my season in a nutshell.

"I know it's frustrating for Anne [coach Donovan]. She has
one of the best teams on paper but everyone's injured. Yet we're
making this amazing run right now."

The Storm, vying for the fourth and final playoff spot in the
West, had won three in a row, all on the road.

Tiffani Johnson led the Storm with 15 points.

Despite a mix of inexperience and injuries, the Storm still made
a late run at the Shock, getting within 64-59 with 4:10 left on a
basket by Ashley Robinson. But the Shock buckled down on defense
for Seattle's next two possessions. Sue Bird tried a 14-footer in
the lane but Ruth Riley swatted it away. Next time down the Storm
threw it away.

The Shock put away the game with 2:57 left on a basket by Ford
to make it 68-59. The Shock, who have had impressive wins over
Sacramento and Los Angeles during this win streak, have the
third-best road record in the league at 8-5.

"We saw this as a championship-type playoff game," Nolan said.
"We wanted to come in and run them because that's what we do. We
also knew that Jackson wasn't 100 percent so we wanted to play good
defense on her and make sure she stayed out of the game. She and
Sue Bird."

Bird missed 10-of-12 attempts and finished with five points and
matched her season high with six turnovers.

The Shock broke from a 23-all score at the end of the first
period to outscore the Storm 23-16 in the second quarter for a
46-39 lead. Nolan made 10-of-16 attempts in the half.

Detroit has already clinched a playoff berth and is second in
the Eastern Conference. The Storm, just off a 3-1 road trip, are
vying for the fourth and final playoff spot in the West. They have
lost four of their past six home games.
